This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it focuses on convolutional neural networks (CNNs) which are widely used in computer vision tasks. Additionally, the paper discusses the role of striding in CNNs, which is a common technique used in computer vision to reduce the spatial dimensions of feature maps. 

The paper also touches on the topic of machine learning (cs.LG) as it discusses the reduction of training complexity through parameter sharing among channels. 

Neural networks (cs.NE) is another likely sub-category as CNNs are a type of neural network and the paper discusses the theoretical representation of CNNs with and without striding. 

Artificial intelligence (cs.AI) is also a possible sub-category as CNNs are a popular tool in AI research and the paper discusses the mathematical role of striding in CNNs. 

Finally, natural language processing (cs.CL) is a less likely sub-category as the paper does not directly relate to language processing, but it does offer a new mathematical perspective on the role of striding which could potentially be applied to other areas of machine learning, including NLP.
